<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09155h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09155h">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09155h"> 155(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> debt of nature</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Penetrating their fog of metaphor I find this &ldquo;die = pay&rdquo; analogy is the same as our English &ldquo;the <mark>debt of nature</mark>&rdquo; equating &ldquo;to die.&rdquo; Thus it is, as death looms ahead, the superlative sum to be paid by every mortal alive, and as the lesser is contained in the greater, so through life all smaller sums &ldquo;paid&rdquo; are only minor &ldquo;deaths&rdquo; compared with <i>the</i> debt, <i>the</i> death, last and largest of all. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 168</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
